  <description type="morphology">Plants 30–100 cm. Stems with 20–85 leaves or leafy bracts proximal to heads. Leaves: basal and proximal cauline usually narrowly lanceolate-spatulate, sometimes broader, mostly 100–500 × 25–50(–55) mm, glabrous or hirtello-puberulent (gland-dotted). Heads usually 9–20. Florets 30–80.</description>
  <description type="phenology">Flowering Aug–Sep(–Oct).</description>
  <description type="habitat">Prairies, glades, open woods, bluff ledges, railroads, rocky limestone soils, red clays, jack pine, pine-oak, oak-juniper, oak-hickory, aspen;</description>
  <description type="elevation">100–500 m;</description>
  <description type="distribution">Ark., Ill., Ind., Mich., Mo., N.Y., Ohio, Pa., W.Va., Wis.</description>
  <number>35b.</number>
  <discussion>Plants of var. nieuwlandii are usually relatively tall and have relatively numerous, even-sized, densely arranged, lanceolate cauline leaves.</discussion>
